      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-10T18:01:36Z",
      "webTitle":"Lampedusa victims include mother and baby attached by umbilical cord",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/10/lampedusa-victims-mother-baby-umbilical-cord",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/2013/oct/10/lampedusa-victims-mother-baby-umbilical-cord",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"25",
        "trailText":"As death toll from migrant boat sinking rises to more than 300 rescuers recount horror of finding pair in prow of vessel",
        "headline":"Lampedusa victims include mother and baby attached by umbilical cord",
        "body":"<p><strong> </strong></p><p>Italian divers recovering the bodies of migrants who <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/03/lampedusa-boat-tragedy-italy-migrants\" title=\"\">died in their hundreds off the coast of Lampedusa</a> last week have said they found a baby boy still attached to his mother by the umbilical cord among the victims.</p><p>As the death toll from the tragedy rose to at least 309, with seven bodies recovered on Thursday morning, rescuers spoke of their horror at discovering the pair earlier this week. \"We could not believe it. We started to cry. My mask was flooded with tears,\" Renato Sollustri, a police diver, told La Repubblica.</p><p>The victims died when a boat packed with around 500 African migrants caught fire and sank around half a mile from the Italian island last Thursday.</p><p>José Manuel Barroso, president of the European commission, visited Lampedusa this week and said he would never forget the sight of \"hundreds of coffins lined up\" in the airport hangar being used temporarily to store the bodies.</p><p>Rescuers said that the baby had been placed in the same coffin as his mother, who is believed to have been about 20 years old. The two were found in the prow of the boat, and were only discovered by Sollustri and his team after they broke through what he described as \"a wall of bodies\", including a woman pressing a young child to her chest and a teenage boy with a T-shirt emblazoned with the word 'Italia'. Then they saw the woman.</p><p>\"We could not have gone back up without trying to do something for her,\" he said. \"We took her out of the boat forming a human chain with our arms. Then we laid her on the seabed. We tied her with a rope to other bodies and then … we rose with them from the depths of the sea to the light.\"</p><p>It was only then that they realised that the woman had, nestling in her clothes, a baby, presumed to have been born during the voyage from the Libyan coast.</p><p>\"Confronted with that woman and her little baby who had just been born we lost our detachment,\" said Sollustri. \"In the many years that I have been doing this job I had never seen anything like that.\"</p><p>As the recovery efforts continued, the ramifications of the disaster dominated political debate in Italy.</p><p>On Wednesday night the justice committee in the upper house of parliament, or Senate, approved an amendment to a 2009 law that made illegal immigration a crime punishable with a fine of up to €10,000 (£8,500).</p><p>Because of that law, the 155 survivors of last week's disaster are under criminal investigation. During a visit to Lampedusa on Wednesday, prime minister Enrico Letta said he felt \"deep shame at such [judicial] zeal\".</p><p>The amendment – presented by two MPs for the anti-establishment Five Star Movement (M5S) – is understood to have the backing of Letta's government. But it will still have to be voted through in both houses of parliament, and support is by no means unanimous.</p><p>In a tweet, justice undersecretary Cosimo Ferri said he supported the repeal of the law because the criminal penalty was \"disproportionate and unjustified\" – let alone impractical given the poverty in which the migrants usually arrive.</p><p>But that view was not shared by some on the centre-right. Mariastella Gelmini, a former minister under Silvio Berlusconi, tweeted: \"The crime of illegal immigration abolished in the justice commission? Have we gone mad?\"</p><p>And, while the proposal began with two M5S senators, it was harshly criticised by their figurehead, Beppe Grillo, and movement guru Gianroberto Casaleggio, neither of whom are elected to parliament.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.beppegrillo.it/en/2013/10/the_crime_of_clandestinity.html\" title=\"\">In an angry blog</a>, they said they agreed with neither the senators' method nor the substance of their amendment.</p><p>\"Substituting oneself for public opinion, the popular wish, is common practice among the parties which want to 'educate' the citizens, but it is not ours,\" they wrote, criticising the MPs for having acted on a policy which was not in M5S electoral manifesto and which had not been consulted on.</p><p>They added that the policy itself would be \"an invitation to migrants from Africa and the Middle East to set sail for Italy … How many illegals are we able to receive if one Italian in eight does not have money to eat?\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419634463|2013-10-16T15:58:10Z|9de37c140c1e59e5e4b983bb4babe9aa64f3de38 -->",
